We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to: 

Direct the Municipal Accountant’s Office, General Services Office and MPDC to properly reconcile their records to ascertain the reliability and validity of the balances reflected in the financial statements, and submit reports which are thoroughly reviewed to ensure reporting consistency, data reliability and comparability. Furthermore, these three departments should have proper communication, e.g., by having effective data access/sharing, to avoid any further unreconciled items as well as deviations in asset classifications among reports;  

Direct the Municipal Accountant’s Office and Municipal General Services Office to carefully take into consideration the proper treatment of the significant amount of unserviceable, lost and demolished properties noted. Persons accountable for those lost properties must be correctly established to act out necessary measures as well as to provide the appropriate accounting entry and avoiding direct derecognition of assets from the books of accounts.  Direct the Municipal General Services Officer to prepare and submit request for technical evaluation of disposal for unserviceable properties and request for relief of accountability (in the case of loss of property) in a timely manner for a prompt response from the concerned agency; and

Direct the Municipal Accountant’s Office and General Services to revisit the guidelines and procedures for one-time cleansing of PPE account balances specifically in the conduct of physical count of PPE, recognition of PPE items found at the station, and disposition for non-existing or missing PPE items, per COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, and to finally address the non-establishment of the accuracy of the PPE balances presented in the financial statements;

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Designate a General Service Officer to take custody of and be responsible for all properties of the Municipality;
Require the Municipal Accountant’s Office (MAO), General Services Office (GSO), as well as the Inventory Committee to revisit COA Circular No. 2020-006 on the guidelines and procedures in the conduct of one-time cleansing of PPE account balances;
Direct the MAO and GSO to carefully take into consideration the proper treatment of the significant amount of unserviceable, lost and demolished properties noted. The General Services Officer is advised to apply for disposal of unserviceable properties, request relief for accountability with COA, in the case of lost properties, and provide proof of authorization of the local legislative bodies to transfer government property. Persons accountable for lost properties must be established before taking the necessary measures. The Municipal Accountant ought to avoid dropping PPE from the Municipality’s books without the conduct of proper disposal procedures, obtaining COA’s approval to credit for losses of property, or attaching the authorization by local legislative bodies to transfer government property; and
Direct the MAO and MPDC to reconcile their records to ascertain the reliability and validity of the CIP accounts reflected in the financial statements and submit reports that are thoroughly reviewed to ensure reporting consistency, data reliability and comparability.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:

Direct the BAC Secretariat to fully utilize the PhilGEPS via posting the necessary Invitation to Bid, Notice of Award, Perfected Contract and Notice to Proceed for each of the Municipality’s procurement to promote transparency and efficiency;

Direct the BAC not to resort to Alternative Mode of Procurement in the absence of conditions provided in 2016 RIRR of RA 9184 that would justify employing such mode of procurement;

Direct the BAC to stop implementation of Infrastructure Projects by Administration when the requirements set forth in the RIRR were not met;

Direct the Technical Working Group to properly evaluate the financial, technical and legal capability of the bidders to provide the HOPE with an appropriate recommendation of determining a qualified supplier, contractor or consultant; and

Direct the BAC to properly and completely fill out the documents related to procurements and to avoid tampering of such to shed out doubt as to authenticity of the said documents. Direct the BAC and all the Municipality personnel to strictly adhere to the provisions of RA 9184 and its 2016 IRR for the Municipality to meet the principles of transparency, accountability, equity, efficiency and economy in its procurement process.

Recommendation:
We have recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:
Direct the Revenue Collecting Officers and Municipal Treasurer to ensure that their respective collections be remitted and deposited intact and daily or in the frequency prescribed by regulation;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to monitor unremitted collections and require Revenue Collecting Officers to remit collections with properly accomplished RCDs as required under Sections 63 and 66 of the GAM for LGU;
Prepare a report on the cancelled AF 56 providing all the details of the error committed; and
Comply with the provisions of COA Circular No. 92-382 and Sections 63 and 66 of Government Accounting Manual for Local Government Units.

Recommendation
We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:
Direct the Petty Cash Custodian to replenish the PCF upon reaching 75% utilization so that sufficient cash balance is available to cover expenses of small payments of the agency;
Prepare a separate Petty Cash Voucher for each transaction and ensure the attachment of complete and acceptable supporting documents;
Request official receipts for purchases made from online stores; and
Avoid charging regular expenses from the Petty Cash Fund.

Recommendation
We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:
Direct the Municipal Treasurer, Disbursing Officer, and other employees with cash advances to return intact and immediately upon liquidation the amount to be refunded pursuant to Item 5.7 of COA Circular 97-002;
Direct the Disbursing Officer to strictly require employees claiming salaries and wages to sign the payroll before releasing the cash;
Direct the Disbursing Officer to require authority from the claimant and identification documents if claimed by person other than the payee, to prepare the necessary report reflecting the total amount disbursed and the breakdown of the unclaimed salaries and wages;
Direct the Disbursing Officer to ensure refunded amounts are remitted to collecting officer with the corresponding official receipt issued thereupon;
Refrain from resorting to cash advances for the procurement of supplies and materials by judiciously planning the procurements of the LGU, and strictly adhere with the provisions of COA Circular 97-002 in granting cash advances and RA 9184 in the procurement of supplies and materials; and
Strictly avoid incurring irregular and unnecessary expenses as provided under COA Circular 2012-003 dated October 29, 2012.

Recommendation:
We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:
Establish guidelines or limitations on the granting of financial assistance to indigents and distressed individuals/families for fair and equitable spread of funds to many beneficiaries by creating a standard policy patterned after the guidelines provided by the DSWD;
Provide written justification on disbursing beyond the allotted budget as provided in the Annual Budget of the LGU, issuing checks in the name of the deceased individuals, providing assistance without complete supporting documents;
Submit complete documentation to establish the legality and validity of the claims such as, but not limited to, a copy of valid identification documents, certified copy of death certificates, certification from the Municipal Health Officers for medical claims, certificate of residency, etc.; and
Be guided by Section 335 of RA 7160, relevant provisions of PD 1445, and COA Circular 2012-003 on the grants and disbursements of funds that are contrary or not allowed pursuant to laws, rules and regulations.

Recommendation:
We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:
Direct the concerned Municipality personnel, in coordination with the BAC, to meticulously and judiciously plan the Municipality’s Annual Procurement to avoid inconvenience and significant delays of the implementation of the Municipality’s Project, Program and Activities thereby improving the Municipality government’s delivery of public service;
Direct the BAC Secretariat to fully utilize the PhilGEPS via posting the necessary Invitation to Bid, Notice of Award, Perfected Contract and Notice to Proceed for each of the Municipality’s procurement to promote transparency and efficiency;
Direct the BAC Secretariat to meet its function and responsibility as the main support unit of the BAC for efficient processing of the Municipality’s procurement;
Direct the BAC not to resort to Alternative Mode of Procurement in the absence of conditions provided in 2016 RIRR of RA 9184 that would justify employing such mode of procurement;
Direct the BAC to stop implementation of Infrastructure Projects by Administration when the requirements set forth in the RIRR were not met;
Direct the Technical Working Group to properly evaluate the financial, technical and legal capability of the bidders to provide the HOPE with an appropriate recommendation of determining a qualified supplier, contractor or consultant;
Direct the BAC to properly and completely fill out the documents related to procurements and to avoid tampering of such to shed out doubt as to authenticity of the said documents; and
Direct the BAC and all the Municipality personnel to strictly adhere to the provisions of RA 9184 and its 2016 IRR for the Municipality to meet the principles of transparency, accountability, equity, efficiency and economy in its procurement process.

